In this homework we will use the mpg data set, you can access the data by loading the package ggplot2 into your R session by executing the command library(ggplot2). The mpg data includes information about fuel economy of popular car models for the years 1999 and 2008 as collected by the US Environmental Protection Agency.

  1. Using the ggplot2 package create a scatterplot of hwy and cty and describe the relationship. Why are there so few points visible? Use a geom that helps reduce the amount of overplotting in the scatterplot. (Try ?geom_jitter)
ggplot(data = mpg, aes(x = hwy, y = cty)) +
  geom_jitter()

# The relationship between the two columns shows that as one increases so does the other, they are strongly correlated.
  1. Apart from the US, most countries use fuel consumption (fuel consumed over fixed distance) rather than fuel economy (distance traveled with fixed amount of fuel). How could you convert cty and hwy into the European standard of liter/100 km? Introduce corresponding variables into the mpg data.
mpg$cty.convert = 235.21 / mpg$cty
mpg$hwy.convert = 235.21 / mpg$hwy
# To convert from miles per gallon to liter/100km, divide 235.21 by the number of miles per gallon
  1. Are cars in 2008 more fuel efficient than cars in 1999? Expand on your answer in (3) for a visual approach to this question. Note: you are not asked to find numeric answers. Instead, interpret plots.
mpg2008 = filter(mpg, year == 2008)
mpg1999 = filter(mpg, year == 1999)

mpg2008 %>% ggplot(aes(x = cty, y = hwy)) +
  geom_jitter() +
  ggtitle("Fuel Efficiency of Cars in 2008")

mpg1999 %>% ggplot(aes(x = cty, y = hwy)) +
  geom_jitter() +
  ggtitle("Fuel Efficiency of Cars in 1999")

# The cars in 2008 are more fuel efficient in comparison to the cars in 1999. The scatterplots show more concentration o the lower part of the graph for the 1999 year while the 2008 plot shows more concentration higher up. Thus the 2008 cars are more fuel efficient.
  1. Use the ggplot2 package to create side-by-side boxplots of cty by class. Describe the relationship in 2-3 sentences. Change the label for the y-axis to ‘city miles per gallon’ (see ?ylab).
ggplot(data = mpg, aes(x = class, y = cty)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  ylab("City miles per gallon")

# The relationship between the mileage and the type of car is shown in the box plot. The larger cars such as SUV, Pickup, and minivan show a lower miles per gallon in comparison to the smaller compact cars. The smaller cars seem to be more fuel efficient in comparison to the larger ones. The subcompact car also has a larger range of miles per gallon, there are a good amount of subcompact cars that have higher and lower miles per gallon.
